Data Cleaning¶

In [130]:
# remove first two rows, which are not relevant
df = df_raw.loc[2:]
df.index = range(len(df))

# sepertate Date into two columns, indicating start and end of poll period
df['date_start'] = df.Date.str.extract('(^\\d+/\\d+)', expand=True)
df['date_end'] = df.Date.str.extract('(\\d+/\\d+$)', expand=True)

# add the year to the dates
df['date_start'].loc[:220] = '2016/' + df['date_start'].loc[:220]
df['date_start'].loc[221:] = '2015/' + df['date_start'].loc[221:]
df['date_end'].loc[:220] = '2016/' + df['date_end'].loc[:220]
df['date_end'].loc[221:] = '2015/' + df['date_end'].loc[221:]

# convert date columns into datetime format
df['date_start'] = pd.to_datetime(df.date_start, format = '%Y/%m/%d')
df['date_end'] = pd.to_datetime(df.date_end, format = '%Y/%m/%d')

# rename and select the columns needed
df = df.rename(columns = {'Clinton (D)':'clinton', 'Trump (R)':'trump'})
df['spread'] = df.clinton - df.trump
df = df[['Poll','date_start','date_end','clinton','trump','spread']]

Time Series Tranformation¶

In [450]:
# create a new time series dataframe, which has dates for everday from the poll table. 
time_series = pd.DataFrame()
time_series['date'] = pd.date_range(start = min(df['date_start']), end = max(df['date_end']), freq='D')
time_series['clinton'] = 0.0
time_series['trump'] = 0.0
time_series['clinton_smooth'] = 0.0
time_series['trump_smooth'] = 0.0
In [451]:
# for each date in the time series, take mean results for all polls that cover this date.
for i in range(len(time_series)):
    df_temp = df.loc[df.date_start <= time_series.date[i]]
    df_select = df_temp.loc[df.date_end >= time_series.date[i]]
    if len(df_select) == 0: # if no poll covers the date, use the results from last day.
        time_series.clinton[i] = time_series.clinton[i-1]
        time_series.trump[i] = time_series.trump[i-1]
    else:
        time_series.clinton[i] = df_select.clinton.mean()
        time_series.trump[i] = df_select.trump.mean()
    
# smooth the results by applying the rolling mean from 10 days ago to 10 days later.
for i in range(len(time_series)):
    time_series.clinton_smooth[i] = time_series.clinton[max(0,i-10):min(len(time_series)-1, i+10)].mean()
    time_series.trump_smooth[i] = time_series.trump[max(0,i-10):min(len(time_series)-1, i+10)].mean()
time_series = time_series[time_series.date >= "2015-07-01"]

# calculate the spread based on clinton and trump results without smoothing.
time_series['spread'] = time_series.clinton - time_series.trump

# the function to test the stationarity, obtained from other source.
def test_stationarity(timeseries):   
    #Determing rolling statistics
    rolmean = pd.rolling_mean(timeseries, window=80)
    rolstd = pd.rolling_std(timeseries, window=80)

    #Plot rolling statistics:
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
    orig = plt.plot(timeseries, color='blue',label='Original')
    mean = plt.plot(rolmean, color='red', label='Rolling Mean')
    std = plt.plot(rolstd, color='black', label = 'Rolling Std')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title('Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation')
    plt.show()
    
    #Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
    print 'Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:'
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries, autolag='AIC')
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','#Lags Used','Number of Observations Used'])
    for key,value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print dfoutput

# forcast the spread for the next 20 days. 
n_steps = 20
date_forcast = [time_series.index.max() + relativedelta(days=x) for x in range(0,n_steps)]

future['forecast'] = results.forecast(steps=n_steps, alpha=0.05)[0]
spread_forcast = pd.concat([spread_analysis, future])
spread_forcast = spread_forcast[-40:]
